{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538796"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16343"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16343"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.17,0.05,0.08,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1636"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"10951"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with vaginal bleeding at 12 weeks gestation in her first pregnancy. She reports passing some tissue. She has experienced intermittent spotting for the past two weeks but no pain. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. Her booking blood pressure was 110/70 mmHg at eight weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Speculum examination reveals a small amount of dark blood in the vaginal vault with a closed cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound shows an enlarged uterus with a heterogeneous mass containing multiple small cystic spaces. Fetal parts are visible. Quantitative beta-HCG is 95,000 IU/L (expected range at 12 weeks: 25,000-288,000).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choriocarcinoma","Complete molar pregnancy","Missed miscarriage","Retained products of conception","Partial molar pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several features typical of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial molar pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E. The ultrasound findings of a heterogeneous mass with cystic spaces and visible but abnormal fetal parts are characteristic. The beta-HCG level, while elevated, is within the expected range for gestational age, which is typical for partial molar pregnancies. In contrast to complete molar pregnancies, partial moles usually have lower beta-HCG levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete molar pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with much higher beta-HCG levels, often above the expected range for gestational age. On ultrasound, complete moles show a \u0027grape-like\u0027 appearance without fetal parts, and patients often have more pronounced symptoms including hyperemesis and early pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMissed miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E would show an non-viable fetus or empty gestational sac on ultrasound, without the characteristic cystic changes in the placental tissue. Beta-HCG levels would typically be lower than expected for gestational age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a malignant form of gestational trophoblastic disease that usually presents after a normal pregnancy, molar pregnancy, or miscarriage. It typically presents with irregular vaginal bleeding and markedly elevated beta-HCG levels, often with evidence of metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetained products of conception\u003C/strong\u003E following a miscarriage would show heterogeneous tissue within the uterus on ultrasound, but would not have the characteristic cystic changes seen in this case. Beta-HCG levels would typically be declining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive diagnosis of partial molar pregnancy is made by histopathological examination of the evacuated tissue, which would show triploidy (69 chromosomes) and focal hydropic changes in the placental villi with trophoblastic proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Partial molar pregnancy typically presents with lower beta-HCG levels compared to complete molar pregnancy.","Ultrasound findings in partial molar pregnancy include focal cystic changes in the placenta and fetal parts may be visible.","Histopathological examination showing triploidy confirms the diagnosis of partial molar pregnancy."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Gestational Trophoblastic Disease (Green-top Guideline No. 38). London: RCOG; 2020 [cited 2024 Nov 24]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/gestational-trophoblastic-disease-green-top-guideline-no-38/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T18:3